In [120]:
#here ae are analysing the change of routes and behaviour after experiencing a crime or being afraid of a crime
changeofbehaviour = gautengH[['Q1119Changed', 'Q1717Changebehaviour']]
avoidroute = gautengH[['Q11204Avoid']]
Routes = gautengS[['Q21a93ChangRoute']] 

# Selecting a count of all the yes and No responses for each colimn
yes = changeofbehaviour[changeofbehaviour == 1] .count() .sum()
no  = changeofbehaviour[changeofbehaviour == 2] .count() .sum()
yes1 = avoidroute[avoidroute == 1] .count() .sum()
no1  = avoidroute[avoidroute == 2] .count() .sum()
yes2 = Routes[Routes == 1] .count() .sum()
no2 = Routes[Routes == 2] .count() .sum()

#Adding all the yes responses and all the no responses
yes = yes + yes1 + yes2
no = no + no1 + no2
plot = yes, no

labels = ['Yes', 'No']
color = ['palegreen','crimson']

# Ploting it into a pie chart
plt.pie(plot, labels =labels, autopct='%1.0f%%', colors = color)
plt.title('How Many Poeple Changed Routes and Behaviour')
fig = plt.gcf()
fig.set_size_inches(10,10)
plt.show()

In [136]:
def freqCount(region, topic_code, response_code):
    return region.groupby(topic_code).size().reset_index(name = 'frequency')['frequency'][response_code]

def multiFreqCount(region, occur_codes, response):
    crime_count = []
    for topic in occur_codes:
        crime_count.append(freqCount(gautengH, topic, response))
        
    return crime_count

plt.rcdefaults()
fig, fc = plt.subplots()

# Example data
y_pos = np.arange(len(crime_labels))

fc.barh(y_pos, multiFreqCount(gautengH, feared_codes, 0))
fc.set_yticks(y_pos)
fc.set_yticklabels(crime_labels)
fc.invert_yaxis()  # labels read top-to-bottom
fc.set_xlabel('Occurance')
fc.set_ylabel('Crimes Feared')
fc.set_title('Most feared crimes')
plt.show()

These are the crimes that people think occur most in their area.¶

plt.rcdefaults()
fig, fc = plt.subplots()

# Example data
y_pos = np.arange(len(crime_labels))

fc.barh(y_pos, multiFreqCount(gautengH, occur_codes, 0), color='red')
fc.set_yticks(y_pos)
fc.set_yticklabels(crime_labels)
fc.invert_yaxis()  # labels read top-to-bottom
fc.set_xlabel('Occurance')
fc.set_title('Most frequently occuring crimes')
plt.show()

The perception is that Housebreaking is the most frequently occuring crime, followed by Street Robbery (Mugging), Home Robbery and Bag Snatching.¶

NB:

  • Housebreaking is when a burglary occurs when there is no one in the house.
  • Home robbery is when there are people present in the house while the crime occurs.
